page.title: 19HOUSING
page.content: The majority of{housing}built between 1890 and 1970.Victorian and Edwardian terraces are near the station.Larger detached houses with big gardens are in quieter secluded roads further from the centre. Some are now used for flats, hotels and other purposes.There are three main{estates,}all on city outskirts: Weeke (council housing) (1950s), Teg Down (1960s), Harestock (1970s). Many of these houses are semi detached with small/medium gardens. Most post 1960 houses have garages. During the last 20 years there has been infilling. Brick and tile are the main building materials. Often people move house within Winchester.Harestock & Weeke are popular with house buyers because of the good{communications}and {services.}Some very old houses still exist in old village centre of Weeke. Also a little 1930s ribbon development
